SIMULATION PLOT EXPLANATIONS
Surface-Proximate Drone Docking Project — Sean Dai
================================================================================

This file documents every plot produced during Phases 1 and 2 of the simulation.
Each plot has explanations on what it shows, which script produced it, what the key findings
are, and any unexpected or noteworthy data points I encountered when conducting virtual simulations. 

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PLOT 1: hover_error.png — Hover Position Error
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

WHAT IT SHOWS
Two-panel figure. Top panel: absolute x-axis (horizontal) position error over
15 seconds. Bottom panel: absolute z-axis (vertical) position error over the
same window. Both panels mark the 5 cm success threshold as a green shaded
band.

SCRIPT
Produced by visualize.py → plot_hover_error()
Data source: Experiment 1 (run_sim.py, exp1_hover_nowall block)
Wall disturbance: OFF. Target: (x=1.0m, z=1.5m). Start: (x=1.2m, z=1.5m).

FINDINGS
The controller passes the Phase 1 success criterion. z-error converges to below
5 cm almost immediately (within the first 0.5 seconds) and stays there for the
full run — the cascaded PD controller handles altitude trivially. x-error starts
at 0.20m and decays gradually, entering the 5 cm band at around t=8s and
continuing to converge toward ~1 cm by t=15s. No sustained oscillation in
either axis.

UNEXPECTED / NOTEWORTHY
The x-error convergence is visibly slower than z-error and shows a mild
overdamped shape rather than a sharp exponential decay. This is because the
horizontal channel uses high derivative gain (kd_x=10.0) which slows the
approach to reduce overshoot: a deliberate design choice to prevent the drone
from overshooting the target position and getting too close to the wall. The
asymmetry between x and z convergence rates is expected but striking visually.

The z-error being essentially zero from t=0 is because the drone starts at
z=1.5m, which is already the target altitude, so the controller has no altitude
error to correct. The tiny residual visible at the start is numerical noise from
the RK45 integrator initialising.

