PLOT 2: trajectory.png — Drone Trajectory (x and z over time)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

WHAT IT SHOWS
Two-panel figure. Top panel: x position (horizontal, toward wall) over 30
seconds with the wall and d_min marked as reference lines. Bottom panel: z
position (vertical altitude) over the same window.

SCRIPT
Produced by visualize.py → plot_trajectory()
Data source: Likely from a near-wall hover or approach experiment (Experiment 2
or 3). Wall disturbance: ON.

FINDINGS
The x trajectory shows the drone approaching the wall from x=1.5m, reaching
a maximum of about x=1.85m (d=0.15m from wall), then oscillating. The
oscillations are caused by the wall disturbance model where the attractive force
pulls the drone toward the wall, the controller pushes back, producing a
limit-cycle oscillation that neither grows nor decays. The drone never
crosses d_min (x=1.95m), confirming the physical safety boundary is respected
in this run.

The z trajectory is interesting: it shows a slow monotonic rise from z=1.50m to
z=1.62m over the first 15 seconds, then similar gentle oscillation around
1.60m. This vertical drift is caused by the wall's thrust modification
(Gamma > 1.0): the wall boosts effective thrust, so the same thrust command
produces more lift, pushing the drone slightly upward. The controller corrects
for this but with some steady-state offset due to the finite integral gain.

UNEXPECTED / NOTEWORTHY
The slow upward vertical drift was not immediately obvious from the equations.
It is a direct consequence of Gamma(d) > 1. When the drone is near the wall,
the effective thrust exceeds commanded thrust, and the altitude loop sees this
as excess lift. In hardware, this will appear as an altitude creep when hovering
near a wall, which the PX4 controller will need to compensate. This is one of
the key reasons why the disturbance residual sub-margin Mr exists in my project — it captures
exactly this discrepancy between commanded and effective thrust.

