PLOT 3: disturbance.png — Wall Disturbance Model
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

WHAT IT SHOWS
Two-panel figure. Top panel: wall disturbance force f_wall (N) plotted against
wall distance d (m). Bottom panel: thrust modification factor Gamma(d) plotted
against wall distance.

Note: the top panel shows a loop/orbit pattern rather than a clean curve
because it is plotted parametrically from a time-series run: the drone
oscillates back and forth near the wall, tracing the same force-distance
relationship repeatedly in both directions with slightly different velocities
each pass (due to vn-dependent terms in the disturbance model).

SCRIPT
Produced by visualize.py → plot_disturbance()
Data source: Near-wall experiment with wall disturbance ON.

FINDINGS
f_wall is consistently negative (attractive toward wall) at all distances shown
(0.25m to 0.48m). The force magnitude ranges from about -0.3N to -0.5N in this
distance band. This confirms the pressure-attraction term (c0) dominates at
these distances.

Gamma ranges from about 1.071 at d=0.47m to 1.101 at d=0.27m — an
approximately 10% thrust boost at the closest approach distance. This is modest
but not negligible: at m=1.0kg hover thrust of 9.81N, a 10% boost means 0.98N
of extra lift that the controller must counteract.

UNEXPECTED / NOTEWORTHY
The loop pattern in the top panel is genuinely interesting. The orbit shape
(wider on the left at closer distances, narrower on the right) shows that the
hysteresis in the disturbance force depends on approach direction. When the
drone is closing (negative vn), the viscous damping term c1 adds to the
attractive force, making it stronger. When retreating (positive vn), the same
term subtracts, making the force weaker. This creates the asymmetric orbit
shape visible in the plot. This hysteresis is physically real and will appear
in hardware measurements — it means the system identification experiment for
c0, c1, c2 must be done in both approach and retreat directions to capture the
full model.

