PLOT 4: margins.png — Dockability Margin and Six Sub-Margins
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

WHAT IT SHOWS
Two-panel figure. Top panel: all six individual sub-margins (Md, Mv, Mdelta,
Momega, Mu, Mr) plotted over 30 seconds, colour-coded. Bottom panel: the
overall Dockability Margin M = min of all six, with M_safe, M_dock, and
M_abort threshold lines marked.

SCRIPT
Produced by visualize.py → plot_margins()
Data source: Near-wall approach or oscillation experiment.

FINDINGS
The overall M oscillates between about 0.15 and 0.70 over the 30 second window,
corresponding to the drone oscillating near the wall. The dominant sub-margin
(the one that most frequently sets the minimum) is Md (clearance, blue). It
drops sharply as the drone approaches and recovers as it retreats, driving most
of the M oscillation.

Mu (control authority, purple) is notably flat around 0.73-0.75 throughout.
This is because T_max = 4*m*g in the simulation, giving 75% headroom at hover
thrust. Notice how the control authority margin is rarely the limiting factor.

Mr (disturbance residual, grey) shows a slow decay from about 0.67 to 0.58
over the run, reflecting the accumulating effect of wall disturbance as the
drone spends more time near the surface.

UNEXPECTED / NOTEWORTHY FINDINGS
Momega (angular rate, dark red) shows brief sharp dips that do not correlate
with the x-position oscillation frequency. These spikes correspond to rapid
attitude corrections the controller makes when the wall force perturbs the
drone sideways: the inner attitude loop fires a large correction, producing
a high instantaneous theta_dot that momentarily drops Momega close to 0. This
is a genuine instability signature that the CBF angular rate damping (Layer 3b)
is designed to suppress.

The plot also shows M briefly touching the M_abort line at around t=14s and
t=26s without triggering abort — this is correct behavior in a No-CBF run
where the abort handler is not active. In a CBF-enabled run, these touches
would trigger a retreat.

