PLOT 7: exp7_permissive_cbf.png — Experiment 7 Initial (Permissive Redesign)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

WHAT IT SHOWS
Two-panel comparison: x(t) top, M(t) bottom. Red = No-CBF, Blue = CBF enabled.
This was the first version of the corrected CBF design with the permissive
architecture, prior to the progressive speed limiting redesign.

SCRIPT
run_sim.py Experiment 7, initial permissive CBF version.
cbf.py with the permissive Layer 3 corrections but before the progressive
speed limiting was added to Layer 3a.

FINDINGS
The top panel shows red (No-CBF) oscillating near x=1.5-1.8m, staying close to
the wall. Blue (CBF) retreats to x=0.0m after abort fires at around t=7-8s and
then oscillates near x=0 for the rest of the run.

The bottom panel shows red M oscillating between 0.05 and 0.30 — deep in the
danger zone. Blue M drops to around 0.15, abort fires, retreats, and then
stabilises at M≈0.73 for the rest of the run after the drone is safely at
x=0.0m.

FINDINGS
The CBF successfully prevented wall collision and M recovered. The abort and
retreat mechanism worked.

UNEXPECTED / NOTEWORTHY
This plot exposed the key design flaw that led to the final redesign. After
retreat, blue stays near x=0.0m for the rest of the simulation (it never
re-approaches the wall). This is wrong by design intent. The abort retreat
should return the drone to the d_safe boundary, allow M to recover, and then
let the controller resume its approach. Instead, the retreat target was set to
x_retreat = wall_x - d_safe = 0.0m and the controller never got a signal to
re-approach after recovery.

This led directly to the progressive speed limiting redesign: instead of
relying on abort to prevent collapse, slow the approach progressively so the
drone can approach the wall deliberately without M collapsing, only triggering
abort for genuine instability. The blue curve sitting at x=0 for 25+ seconds
in this plot was the visual evidence that the design was treating the abort as
a terminal state rather than a transient safety event.

