PLOT 8: exp7_comparison.png — Experiment 7 Intermediate Version
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

WHAT IT SHOWS
Two-panel comparison: x(t) top, M(t) bottom. Red = No-CBF, Blue = CBF enabled.
This is an intermediate iteration of Experiment 7, after a decent amount of fixes but before
the final progressive speed limiting redesign.

SCRIPT
run_sim.py Experiment 7, intermediate version.
An earlier version of cbf.py before the Layer 3a progressive limit was
fully implemented.

FINDINGS
Both runs show oscillation near x=1.4-1.85m: neither drone is staying very
close to the wall. The M curves show both oscillating between about 0.15 and
0.75 in a similar pattern. The two runs look more similar than different in this
version, suggesting CBF corrections were firing but not producing strong
enough differentiation from No-CBF behavior.

The red run touches M_abort briefly (around t=21s) with no retreat — confirming
No-CBF safety action is correctly disabled. The blue run also dips near M_abort
without retreating cleanly in some iterations.

UNEXPECTED / NOTEWORTHY FINDINGS
The similarity of the red and blue curves in this intermediate version was the
diagnostic that revealed the approach speed problem. When the two runs look
nearly the same, it means the CBF is either not firing at all (threshold not
being crossed) or firing so weakly that the physical behavior is unchanged. The
ramp-target approach speed was below the CBF threshold in this version, which is
why both curves look nearly identical. This is what motivated switching from a
ramp target to a fixed target for the final Experiment 7 design — allowing the
PD controller to accelerate the drone naturally and exceed the CBF threshold.

