PLOT 9: exp7_corrected.png — Experiment 7 Final (Corrected Design)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

WHAT IT SHOWS
Two-panel comparison: x(t) top, M(t) bottom. Red = No-CBF, Blue = CBF enabled.
This is the final corrected design with progressive speed limiting in Layer 3a
and the properly gated abort handler.

SCRIPT
run_sim.py Experiment 7, final version.
cbf.py Version 4 with progressive speed limiting in Layer 3a.
Abort handler gated on cbf_on flag. Fixed-target approach design.

FINDINGS
Top panel: Both runs are visually identical from t=0 to about t=7s — both
approach the wall at the same rate to the same position (x≈1.56m). At t≈7s,
the blue run's abort fires and the drone retreats to x≈0.6m (not all the way
to x=0.0m as in earlier versions). After retreating, blue oscillates near the
approach zone. Red has no safety action and continues oscillating near the wall
for the full 25 seconds.

Bottom panel: Red M oscillates between 0.15 and 0.65 — repeatedly touching and
crossing M_abort with no consequence. Blue M drops with the approach, abort
fires just above 0.15, retreats, and M recovers toward 0.6-0.7. The two curves
diverge cleanly at t≈7s.

UNEXPECTED / NOTEWORTHY
The numerically identical trajectories before abort fires (max difference
0.00094m, verified in the verification script) confirm that the permissive CBF
design is working exactly as intended — it does not interfere with deliberate
approach. The CBF is truly invisible until the genuine safety boundary is
approached.

The retreat distance (~1.0m) is notably shorter than the earlier versions where
the drone retreated all the way to x=0.0m. This is because the retreat target
is now set to wall_x - d_safe = 0.0m but the drone decelerates naturally before
reaching it — the controller is working against wall suction and inertia, so it
settles at a closer-than-target equilibrium. This is physically sensible and not
a bug, but it means the actual retreat distance is determined by the dynamics
rather than purely by the target coordinate. In hardware, this means the
effective retreat distance will depend on the real wall disturbance strength —
another reason to get accurate c0, c1, c2 values from system identification
before relying on the abort mechanism in flight tests.

